                   BRITISH SOLAR POWER
Homeowners across the United Kingdom can apply for a 
government grant to cover 50 percent of the costs of
fitting solar panels to their roofs, The British
Broadcasting Corp. reports.  The $30 million government 
program aims to reduce Britain's carbon emissions, bring
down the cost of solar electricity and dispel the myth 
that solar energy is a non-starter in the U.K. climate. 
Kelly Butler, spokeswoman for the agency administering 
the grants, confirms that even with a 50 percent subsidy 
most systems still cost the homeowner about $10,000.
The same government agency says the average savings on 
electric bills would be roughly up to $138 a year and
that it could take 60 years before the savings justify 
the amount invested. 

                     
