                COMPETITION FOR SIDEWALKS
Competition for sidewalk space has been an issue since
Medieval times when pedestrians had to dodge garbage flung 
from buildings. Now 33 states have passed legislation 
allowing Segways -- the $4,950 self-balancing motorized
scooter -- on sidewalks.  However, senior citizen and
pedestrian advocacy groups in San Francisco say the
12.5 mile-per-hour pace of a Segway is a threat to public 
safety and it has been banned from sidewalks -- but allowed 
on streets there, The New York Times reports.  Competing
with the Segway for space on urban sidewalks are: vendors,
rollerbladers, strollers, non-motorized scooters, newspaper
boxes, sidewalk cafes, fruit stands, bus shelters and 
benches. 

                 
